Delta Lake in AWS with Redshift Integration¶

(using AWS EMR, using AWS EMR, Apache Hive Warehouse (aka spark-warehouse) and AW S3)¶

Delta Lake brings ACID transactions to your data lakes. It provides serializability, the strongest level of isolation level.

Time Travel (data versioning):Delta Lake provides snapshots of data enabling developers to access and revert to earlier versions of data for audits, rollbacks or to reproduce experiments

Time travel in Delta improves developer productivity tremendously. It helps:

  • Data scientists manage their experiments better
  • Data engineers simplify their pipelines and roll back bad writes
  • Data analysts do easy reporting

Apache Spark 3.0.and Delta Lake 0.7.0 onwards supporst registering and defining Delta-format tables in Hive Metastore

Redshift Spectrum to Delta Lake integration¶

Amazon Redshift Spectrum adds support for querying open source Delta Lake¶

  • We can now use Amazon Redshift to run read queries against tables in your Amazon S3 data lake with open source Delta Lake.
  • Redshift Spectrum allows to read the latest snapshot Delta Lake (version 0.5.0 & 0.7.0) tables via the manifest files.

Refer to `Creating external tables for Amazon Redshift Spectrum`

Step 1 : Generate manifests of a Delta table using Apache Spark¶
In [10]:
# Generate manifests of a Delta table using Apache Spark
spark.sql("GENERATE symlink_format_manifest FOR TABLE {0}".format(deltaTabName))

DataFrame[]

The generate operation generates manifest files at /_symlink_format_manifest/. In other words, the files in this directory contain the names of the data files (that is, Parquet files) that should be read for reading a snapshot of the Delta table.

Step 2 : Create Redshift external table¶


CREATE EXTERNAL TABLE spectrum_delta.tbldelta_spectrum (id BIGINT)
ROW FORMAT SERDE 'org.apache.hadoop.hive.ql.io.parquet.serde.ParquetHiveSerDe'
STORED AS
INPUTFORMAT 'org.apache.hadoop.hive.ql.io.SymlinkTextInputFormat'
OUTPUTFORMAT 'org.apache.hadoop.hive.ql.io.HiveIgnoreKeyTextOutputFormat'
LOCATION 's3://bucket-name/POC/deltas3/deltaDB/tbldelta/_symlink_format_manifest/';

Query Redshift external delta table¶

The query results from Redshift spectrum external table should be same as above delta table

newData_loc = quotes+delta_tble_s3_path+bkslash+dbName+bkslash+newTabName+bkslash+quotes

          .format(newTable, col1, newData_loc))

spark.sql("SHOW TABLES FROM {} LIKE 'newData'".format(dbName)).show()

print("############# Insert values to table ###############")
spark.sql("INSERT INTO {0} VALUES 3, 4, 5, 6".format(newTable))

print("########### Upsert new data #############")
spark.sql('''MERGE INTO {0} USING {1}
            ON {0}.id = {1}.{2}
            WHEN MATCHED THEN
              UPDATE SET {0}.{2} = {1}.{2}
            WHEN NOT MATCHED THEN INSERT *
        '''.format(deltaTabName, newTable, col1))

print("########### view upsert data #############")
spark.sql("SELECT * FROM {0} ORDER BY {1}".format(deltaTabName, col1)).show()

Update manifests¶

When the data in a Delta table is updated you must regenerate the manifests using either of the following approaches:¶
  • Update explicitly: After all the data updates, you can run the generate operation to update the manifests.
  • Update automatically: You can configure a Delta table so that all write operations on the table automatically update the manifests. To enable this automatic mode, set the corresponding table property using the following SQL command.


The Redshift Spectrum integration has known limitations in its behavior on the mainfest file

Whenever Delta Lake generates updated manifests, it atomically overwrites existing manifest files. Therefore, Redshift Spectrum will always see a consistent view of the data files; it will see all of the old version files or all of the new version files. However, the granularity of the consistency guarantees depends on whether the table is partitioned or not.

  • Refer to Redshift Spectrum Delta lake Limitations
  • Refer to Limitations and troubleshooting for Delta Lake tables

Query Redshift spectrum external table to check if above results are reflected¶

Depending on what storage system you are using for Delta tables, it is possible to get incorrect results when Redshift Spectrum concurrently queries the manifest while the manifest files are being rewritten. In file system implementations that lack atomic file overwrites, a manifest file may be momentarily unavailable. Hence, use manifests with caution if their updates are likely to coincide with queries from Redshift Spectrum

Performance

This is an experimental integration and its performance and scalability characteristics have not yet been tested.

# than the retention interval you plan to specify, you can turn off this safety check by setting 
# the Apache Spark configuration property spark.databricks.delta.retentionDurationCheck.enabled to false.
# You must choose an interval that is longer than the longest running concurrent transaction and
# the longest period that any stream can lag behind the most recent update to the table.

Delta time-travel for large scale datalakes¶

Continuously updating Delta table across multiple downstream jobs¶

Pinned view of a continuously updating Delta table across multiple downstream jobs¶

With VERSION queries, we can now pin the snapshot of a continuously updating Delta table for multiple downstream jobs. Consider a situation where a Delta table is being continuously updated, say every 15 seconds, and there is a downstream job that periodically reads from this Delta table and updates different destinations. In such scenarios, typically we want a consistent view of the source Delta table so that all destination tables reflect the same state. We can now easily handle such scenarios as follows:

In [22]:
# Get recent snapshot version (i.e. lastest minus 1) of delta table into a variable
recent_ver = str((df_Hist.agg({'version': 'max'}).collect()[0][0]-1)) #convert to str
recent_ver = "`"+delta_tbl_loc[1:-1]+ "@v"+recent_ver+"`"

snapData_loc = quotes+delta_tble_s3_path+bkslash+dbName+bkslash+snapshotTable+bkslash+quotes

# Create df for recent snapshot
df_recent = spark.sql("SELECT * FROM delta.{0} ORDER BY {1}".format(recent_ver, col1))

# Register table so it is accessible via SQL Context
df_recent.createOrReplaceTempView("df_recent")

# Drop snapshot tables from pervious run
df_drop = spark.sql("SHOW TABLES IN {0} LIke '{1}*'"
                    .format(dbName, snapshotTable)).select("database","tableName")

rownum=0
for t in df_drop.collect():
    dropTable = (t.database+"."+t.tableName)
    rownum= rownum + 1
    rownumSTR= str(rownum)
    rownumSTR = "["+rownumSTR+"]."
    print(rownumSTR, "Dropping table:", dropTable)
    spark.sql("DROP TABLE IF EXISTS {0}".format(dropTable))

# Create a new snapshot table/s for each unique values

# newData table s3 location
snapData_loc = quotes+delta_tble_s3_path+bkslash+dbName+bkslash+snapshotTable+bkslash+quotes

print("--------------------Create snapshot table/s --------------------")
for i in df_recent.collect():
    snapData_loc_n = "`"+snapData_loc[1:-1]+snapshotTable+str(i.id)+bkslash+"`"
    print("create and populate sanpshot table :",snapshotName+str(i.id))
    spark.sql('''CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS {0} STORED AS PARQUET LOCATION {1}
                 AS SELECT * FROM df_recent WHERE {2} == {3}'''
              .format(snapshotName+str(i.id), snapData_loc, col1, (i.id)))
    
# query Snapshot tables
df_snapshot = spark.sql("SHOW TABLES IN {0} LIke '{1}*'"
                    .format(dbName, snapshotTable)).select("database","tableName")

print("--------------------Query snapshot table/s --------------------")
sqlSTRNew = ''
strUNION = " UNION "
counter=1
RowsNo=df_snapshot.count()

for s in df_snapshot.collect():
    pinTable = s.database + "." + s.tableName
    sqlSTR=("""SELECT '{0}' AS database, '{1}' AS tablName, count({2}) AS rowCount FROM {3}"""
         .format(s.database, s.tableName, col1, pinTable))
    if counter == RowsNo:
      sqlSTRNew = sqlSTRNew +  sqlSTR
    else:
        sqlSTRNew =sqlSTRNew +  sqlSTR + strUNION
    counter = counter+1

# execute SQL
spark.sql(sqlSTRNew).show()

# An exception is thrown if the database does not exist in the system.

# Manually remove the S3 folder used for demo
s3 = boto3.resource('s3')
bucket = s3.Bucket('deltalake-bucket')
bucket.objects.filter(Prefix="POC/deltas3/").delete() #folder to be removed is "PO" & deltas3". Run with caution!!!
